I've been working with 3D since the 1990s and 3D printing since 2013. I built a Rostock MAX delta arm printer from a kit and I've been figuring out how to upgrade it ever since. In 2015, I upgraded to the excellent Rostock MAX METAL from TrickLaser, and I will be building more of them for my fleet. I also do commercial work for clients who need 3D objects printed, and optionally designed. In addition to the paid work and the free objects I release here, I'd also like to branch out into "paid open source," in which someone pays me to create a design and then release it under an open source license.

I also do programming. I implemented a device driver for Adafruit's WS2812 LEDs that runs on the Raspberry Pi. Before this, it was necessary to use an Arduino or some other external chip. It was erroneously believed that the Pi, running Linux, could not time the signal generation accurately enough to be reliable. I knew that the Pi's DMA controller should be up to the job, and sure enough, it is!

Hi, I go by the name 'monos scema', a maker more than a tinkerer, but have been into 3D-Printing since I got my First machine, which is the Anet-A8 in February this year 2018. It;'s definitely been a learning curve, especially having to overcome issues regarding breakdowns and the cost of wasted material. But I can appreciate all the effort that goes into learning 3D-printing now and it's opened my eyes.

The benefit 3D-printing has for me, is the ability to further my creative skills personally and academically, by providing a platform to enjoy the end process to printing and the prototyping aspect to design too.

9 Months in, and I've only just reached the end of upgrading my machine from its basic look to the upgraded personalised version, phase #02.

Thanks to everyone in this verse, who have shared their stuff with us all. so I thought I'd update my profile before presenting my own links to my video's and which files I've used to upgrade my machine...

Next, I'm considering on upgrading my machine to another level, and if so, you all will be one of the first to see it..!

bio:
I actually wrote a lot in this box, but I'm going to have to come back. When I selected A profile image, after it uploaded, it reloaded this page and deleted all of my input. Basically, I'm a patent attorney who offers several engineering in cad services. God, I am bummed to of lost that. I talked about the various projects I'm doing, and the different CAD packages I've used.
Whenever I pick up a new CAD program, the first thing I make is my law-practice logo, which is basically just an intersect of a D and B. A 3-D print of one of the earlier versions is my profile picture. The first time I made it, I did it in tinker cad while volunteering at a Makerfaire booth for Wake robotics, and NC first team in Cary, North Carolina. I was demonstrating sketch up and tinker cad to visitors.

Maaaaaaan, what a bummer. I am not typing that all out again. Maybe I'll come back and add it in. But right now, I've got to get back to work. :-(

You can learn about my practice and read the various things I've read, and see several of my models and engineering stuff that meanders away from strictly patent practice on my website, www.Becker-IP.com. That also redirects to my other URL, www.Beckerpatent.com
I'm also on Twitter at @danbeckr, instagram at @beckeripdotcom, and facebook (search for Becker-ip.com).

I was surprised to not see on shape among the modeling programs. It's my favorite out of all the CAD programs I use, particularly because I can just run it on my phone anytime I have a free second. The other enormous convenience of being able to fly around models with just my fingertips. I think it feels like inventor, but it is friendlier, apart from having to use "anchor points" to do relations in assemblies

The BYU Compliant Mechanisms Research Group (CMR) involves students and faculty who strive to make an impact by creating compliant mechanism theories and applications that are , used by others, and make a difference for good.

We share our work with

  • the research community through technical papers, books, theses and dissertations, hosting visiting scholars, collaborations, and presentations

  • industry and government through research contracts, technology transfer (including intellectual property agreements), presentations, visits, and creating spinoff companies

  • society through maker resources, YouTube videos, books, visits to our lab, presentations, exhibitions, and providing impactful products

The CMR’s educational objective is to provide students with research opportunities of real consequence in a rewarding environment that
increases their technical abilities, confidence, and desire and ability to be an influence for good.

The Multirap M800 from Multec is an industry-standard FFF 3D printer with a solid aluminum chassis, closed design, front door with door protection and emergency stop switch. The design of the Multirap production machine complies with the safety guidelines of the Machinery Directive and the Product Liability Act.
This new technology introduced by the patented 2Move dual print head, for the first time offers the possibility for clean multi material printing with individually controlled nozzles. The integrated anti-drip protection ensures the clean separation of the different materials. Optionally the 4Move print head with 4 nozzles is also available.
The user interface, Multec Host, offers a simple to use touch control interface which gives the user quick access to all important machine functionality for fast and continuously reliable work.
Innovative developments ensure the future viability of Multirap machines. Therefore, new developments can be retrofitted after the fact. The Multirap additive manufacturing systems combine precision, longevity and versatility. They meet all requirements regarding safety, process monitoring and automation as well as reliability for industrial use. 

The Multex4Move provides four distinct improvements on several levels that open up completely new dimensions in the field of 3D printing. Due to the clever design, oozing (dripping during multiple hotend printing) is finally a thing of the past. We achieve this by only allowing our active nozzle to be in direct contact with the model.

Multec is a german company specialized in 3d-printer design for industrial additive production, devlopment of printing materials and new innovative extruder for multiple printing.
Multirap is available as single oder dual printer, and coming soon as quad-extruder with patented anti-oozing design. The printer are designed especially regarding good stiffness and accuracy for working as a milling machine for pcb, plastics and wood, engraving machine as well as a 3D-Printer. It is available in three sizes: 800x650x500 and 480x380x350 and 280x240x240mm.
Have a look at it here: https://www.multec.de/

Please visit http://www.multec.de for additional information. But feel free to ask us for more information.
